<F P=100> INTER-EUROPEAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Delors Calls For World Economic Security Council </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Delors Calls For World Economic Security Council </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0706173194 Paris AFP in English 1556 GMT 7 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0706173194 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Brussels, June 7 (AFP) -- Jacques Delors, chief 
executive of the European Union [EU], called here Tuesday [7 
June] for the creation of an economic security council to 
promote world economic stability. 
  Delors, president of the European Commission, said urgent 
action was needed towards "global management of economic 
problems." 
  He was speaking at the end of a three-day session of the 
Commission on Global Governance, a body comprising 28 men and 
women established by world leaders in 1992 to study global 
cooperation following the end of the Cold War. 
  Delors identified the growing swell of world capital 
movements as a particular threat to economic stability and 
sustainable economic growth. 
  "If the rationale of the capital market goes against the 
interests of the global neighbourhood, who can react?" he asked 
at a press conference. 
  Delors's answer was an economic security council comprising 
the United States, Japan, the EU, China, Russia and countries 
heading regional economic organisation in Africa, Latin America, 
Asia and the Pacific. 
  He proposes that such a council meet regularly with 
representatives of such institutions as the World Bank, the 
International Monetary Fund, the General Agreement on Tariffs 
and Trade and the International Labour Organisation. 
  "We cannot go on talking about the global and the world 
economy without knowing how to tackle the problem," Delors said. 
  He stressed the need to take a global view of a world 
economy 
becoming ever-more unified, and to establish links between 
"trade, currencies, finance, the environment and polulation 
growth." 
  Delors said that the international capital market had to 
bear 
much of the blame for the current rise in longterm interest 
rates. 
  Co-chairing the Commission's meeting were the former 
secretary-general of the Commonwealth, Shridath Ramphal, and 
former Swedish Prime Minister Ingvar Carlsson. 
  They said the meeting had also discussed a United Nations 
peacekeeping force to extinguish flare-ups of violence, and ways 
to make the UN more accountable to ordinary people and 
organisations as well as governments. 
  But Ramphal would not be drawn on what action should be 
taken 
to bring countries such as China into line with international 
standards of human rights. 
  "Good government doesn't need the suppression of one set of 
values in favour of another," he told journalists when asked 
whether the Asian drive towards economic development might clash 
with individual human rights. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

