<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ruehe Comments on Army Volunteers, NATO Growth </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ruehe Comments on Army Volunteers, NATO Growth </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0706212094 Berlin DDP/ADN in German 1639 GMT 7 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0706212094 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DDP/ADN </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Hamburg (DDP/ADN) -- German Defense Minister Volker 
Ruehe has spoken in support of including volunteers in the 
Bundeswehr. Professional associations should be set up to 
represent a high proportion of volunteers alongside professional 
soldiers, Ruehe said in Hamburg this evening. He referred to 
Denmark, where brigades with 5,000 volunteers were already in 
existence for international missions. 
  Ruehe stressed that the Bundeswehr had to become more 
"differentiated" to be deployed in a more versatile way. Belief 
in an army that carries out only one mission is outmoded in view 
of the changed international situation. Ruehe said it was 
"nonsense" to talk of the danger of a two-class army. Every 
section of the armed forces must receive the equipment and 
structure needed for its task. The defense of Germany and the 
Alliance would however remain the main mission of the Bundeswehr. 
  Ruehe spoke in favor of entering into a dialogue with Russia 
and the other CIS states on nuclear security and the 
nonproliferation of nuclear weapons as soon as possible. He was 
confident that there would be an enlarged membership of NATO 
within the framework of the Partnership for Peace by the year 
2000. 

</TEXT>

