<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Press Comments on Kohl-Gonzalez Summit </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Press Comments on Kohl-Gonzalez Summit </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0806120694 Cologne Deutschlandfunk Network in German 0505 
GMT 8 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU0806120694 </F>
<F P=104>  Cologne Deutschlandfunk Network </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the press review] </F>
  [Text] On the subject of the German-Spanish consultations, 
the following can be read in the MITTELDEUTSCHE ZEITUNG of 
Halle: Will European unity soon receive more impetus again? 
The prospects are not bad, because within the next 18 months, 
the Germans, French, and Spaniards will assume the presidency of 
the European Union [EU] one after another. After his talks with 
Spain's Prime Minister Filipe Gonzalez in Schwerin, Chancellor 
Helmut Kohl was already enthusiastic about the troika at the 
head of the EU until the end of 1995. Nevertheless, the 
triple-team will not find things easy, for it will consist of 
large European member-states, and in the past this has 
repeatedly given rise to mistrust, if not opposition, on the 
part of smaller countries, says the MITTELDEUTSCHE ZEITUNG. 
  NEUE ZEIT of Berlin says on this topic: Considering the 
substance of the observations made at the 11th German-Spanish 
consultations, one may be permitted to have doubts. Everyone 
wants the best. Success depends on specifics. But more 
important than all good intentions is the climate this time. It 
was good to bring the Spanish Prime Minister Gonzalez, 
representative of southern interests in the EU, to 
Mecklenburg-Western Pomerania and discuss an eastward expansion 
there as well. The partners must be convinced that this 
expansion does not lead to a German special path, that doing the 
one thing does not automatically mean abandoning the other, the 
consolidation of the EU, says NEUE ZEIT. 
  NEUE OSNABRUECKER ZEITUNG represents the following view: The 
formation of a European triple-team consisting of Germany, 
France, and Spain, announced by Helmut Kohl and Felipe Gonzalez, 
will not encounter unanimous support in every EU country. Above 
all, in Great Britain there is profound suspicion about such a 
troika, but one cannot assume a leadership function if one 
applies the brakes all the time. Without the boost supplied by 
Germany and France, stagnation would have been almost 
inevitable, and there would have been no EU. Also in future, 
the EU needs such pioneers, not bosses, and it is to be 
considered highly positive that Spain is placing itself in this 
group of kinetic forces, says the NEUE OSNABRUECKER ZEITUNG. 

</TEXT>

