<H3> <TI>   Pasqua Announces Dates for Presidential Election </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Pasqua Announces Dates for Presidential Election </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0706170294 Paris AFP in English 1628 GMT 7 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0706170294 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Paris, June 7 (AFP) -- French voters will choose a 
successor to President Francois Mitterrand in a two-round ballot 
next year on April 23 and May 7, Interior Minister Charles 
Pasqua said on Tuesday [7 June]. 
  Setting the date for the presidential ballot, Pasqua told 
the 
French Senate, or upper house, that the Socialist head of 
state's second seven-year term ends at midnight on May 20, 1995. 
  Mitterrand, aged 77, has shrugged aside any idea of standing 
for a third term. 
  First elected head of state in 1981, he has been sharing 
power with a conservative coalition government since the ouster 
of the former Socialist administration in elections in March 
last year. 
  He also shared power with a conservative government from 
1986 
to 1988. 

</TEXT>

