<F P=100> CYPRUS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Mikhailidhis Rejects Continuation of CBM's </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Mikhailidhis Rejects Continuation of CBM's </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC0806083994 Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network in Greek 0700 GMT 8 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC0806083994 </F>
<F P=104>  Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network </F>

<F P=105>  Greek </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Foreign Minister Alekos Mikhailidhis said that if an 
attempt is made for diversion, that is continuing with the 
confidence-building measures [CBM's], after the UN report, we 
will not follow this course. He added: We believe that such a 
development is absolutely unjustified following the content of 
the UN secretary general's significant report. 
  In a statement to CyBC [Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation] 
this 
morning, Mr. Mikhailidhis noted that continuing the discussion 
of the CBM's cannot lead anywhere, it detracts from the report, 
and it can only cause damage. Mr. Mikhailidhis also said that 
some people believe that there is still room for the CBM's and 
reiterated categorically that we would consider it a fatal blow 
to the entire process if we continued something which is already 
obsolete. 
  Concerning a letter that Rauf Denktas conveyed to the United 
Nations, Mr. Mikhailidhis said that Denktas is starting with a 
premise that ise absolutely unacceptable to us and are in 
complete opposition to the UN resolutions. He stressed: 
Neither our side nor the United Nations, through its 
resolutions, have ever accepted the fact that Cyprus can be 
anything but a unitary sovereignty, a unitary citizenship. Mr. 
Mikhailidhis also pointed that Denktas reiterated in his letter 
his well-known demands for partnership, equal participation, and 
separate rights. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

