<F P=100> GREECE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Papoulias on Purpose of Tehran, Istanbul Visits </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Papoulias on Purpose of Tehran, Istanbul Visits </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC0706123494 Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network in 
Greek 1130 GMT 7 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC0706123494 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Greek </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Foreign Minister Karolos Papoulias left for Tehran 
at 1000 today on a two-day visit to Iran. The foreign minister 
will then proceed to Istanbul where he will participate in the 
spring conference of NATO foreign ministers on 9-10 June. 
  In a statement made shortly before leaving for Tehran, the 
foreign minister described these upcoming visits as very 
interesting. Concerning his visit to Iran, Mr. Papoulias 
stressed that it is in the mutual interest of both countries to 
maintain and develop their existing good relations. He added 
that Iran is a strategic area, a regional power with influence 
in the area and that Greek foreign policy is interested in this 
broader region. 
  The foreign minister also noted that he will met with 
Turkish 
Foreign Minister Hikmet Cetin on the sidelines of the NATO 
foreign ministers conference in Istanbul. Responding to a 
journalist's question on whether there has been any Turkish 
reaction to the Patriarchate's demand for greater security and 
what his comment is on this demand, the foreign minister said: 
The demand is certainly justified after the recent terrorist 
attacks against the Patriarchate. You know that the Greek 
Government has reacted strongly in all directions. We also 
protested to the European Union about this situation. I think 
this issue will be one of the main topics of discussion with Mr. 
Cetin. Mr. Papoulias concluded: We certainly have every reason 
to demand this reinforced safety of the Patriarchate. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

