<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Matsunaga, Christopher Discuss DPRK Nuclear Issue </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Matsunaga, Christopher Discuss DPRK Nuclear Issue </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0906023594 Tokyo KYODO in English 0213 GMT 9 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0906023594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Paris, June 9 KYODO -- U.S. Secretary of State 
Warren Christopher and Japanese Government representative Nobuo 
Matsunaga on Wednesday [8 June] agreed that the two nations 
should continue close dialogue on the North Korean nuclear 
issue, Japanese officials said. 
  The agreement came as they held talks at the Organization 
for 
Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD) headquarters in 
Paris. They were attending the two-day OECD ministerial meeting. 
  Christopher expressed strong concern over the situation in 
North Korea. Matsunaga, former ambassador to the United States, 
said the Japanese Government will in principle take concerted 
action if the United States imposes economic sanctions on North 
Korea, the officials said. 
  However, Matsunaga stressed the necessity to maintain 
further 
efforts for a peaceful settlement of the issue, they added. 

</TEXT>

