<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kinkel Rejects Russian Security System </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kinkel Rejects Russian Security System </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0906101494 Berlin DDP/ADN in German 0957 GMT 9 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0906101494 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DDP/ADN </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Bonn (DDP/ADN) -- German Foreign Minister Klaus 
Kinkel (Free Democratic Party) has rejected Russian ideas for a 
European security system. Subordinating NATO to the Conference 
for Security and Cooperation in Europe (CSCE), as Russia has in 
mind, "would run counter to our security interests and is not 
acceptable," Kinkel said today at the NATO foreign ministers' 
spring conference in Istanbul. NATO remained the anchor for 
security and stability in Europe, the advance release of 
Kinkel's speech said. It is important for Russia to take an 
active part in the Partnership for Peace. Over and above that, 
relations should be deepened, Kinkel stressed, calling for the 
meeting to give a signal to that effect to Moscow. However, 
this "by no means meant a directorate of NATO and Russia for 
European security questions." Nor can Russia "receive any kind 
of right of veto over alliance decisions." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

