<F P=100> FRANCE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Clinton-Chirac Meeting Focuses on Drug Problem </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Clinton-Chirac Meeting Focuses on Drug Problem </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BR0806122494 Paris LE FIGARO in French 8 Jun 94 p 6 </F>
<F P=103> BR0806122494 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris LE FIGARO </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Francoise Varenne report: "Clinton-Chirac </F>
Discussions"] 
  [Text] Jacques Chirac [mayor of Paris and Rally for the 
Republic, RPR, president] met yesterday with U.S. President 
Bill Clinton. The half-hour meeting took place in U.S. 
Ambassador Pamela Harriman's residence on the rue du Faubourg 
St. Honore. The mayor of Paris was accompanied by Didier 
Quentin, the city's international relations director, and Pierre 
Lellouche, his foreign policy and defense adviser. Bill 
Clinton's delegation included U.S. Secretary of State Warren 
Christopher and Thomas McLarty, the President's chief of the 
staff. Jacques Chirac and Bill Clinton spent most of the 
meeting discussing international affairs, and in particular the 
Bosnian conflict. On this issue, they were agreed that the arms 
embargo should not be lifted. The RPR president also stressed 
the seriousness of the situation in Algeria, which threatens to 
destabilize the whole Maghreb region. Where nuclear testing is 
concerned, Jacques Chirac stressed the need for France to carry 
out a few more tests before switching over to test simulations. 
For his part, Bill Clinton expressed his concern about the 
growing risk of the proliferation of weapons of mass destruction 
(nuclear, chemical, and bacteriological) and the danger that 
this represents, insofar as they could be used by terrorist 
groups. 
<H5>  Working Group </H5>
  Moreover, Jacques Chirac explained at length to the U.S. 
President his views on the urgent and vital need to tackle the 
narcotics problem at the production stage. In particular, he 
stressed the considerable increase in the production of heroin 
and its consequences, especially for young people. 
  Chirac also underscored the need to define a policy and take 
action, possibly under the aegis of the United Nations, to 
encourage countries producing narcotics to think about promoting 
alternative sources of revenue for their farmers. 
  President Clinton showed much interest in this proposal. The 
two men decided that regular contacts would be established 
between experts on both sides and that a working group would be 
set up to define a policy for the fight against narcotics 
production. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

