<H3> <TI>   Lamassoure Explains Troop Presence in Chad </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Lamassoure Explains Troop Presence in Chad </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0806201694 Paris Radio France International in French 1838 
GMT 8 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0806201694 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris Radio France International </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] After the Libyan withdrawal from the Aouzou Strip 
in Chad, Colonel al-Qadhdhafi demanded that the French troops 
stationed in Chad leave. He believes that their presence is no 
longer justified. Paris does not agree. Minister Alain 
Lamassoure explained this during the traditional question time 
at the National Assembly: 
  [Begin Lamassoure recording] After this withdrawal, an 
agreement, a treaty of friendship and cooperation was signed by 
Chad and Libya, and we also welcomed this. The French troops 
currently in Chad -- what is called the Epervier operation, 
consisting of 800 men -- are there as a result of an agreement 
made with the Chad Government. That government has not asked 
France to modify its operation. Given that fact and given the 
precariousness of the situation in the country and in the 
region, there are no plans either to modify and certainly not to 
reduce this operation for the moment. [end recording] 
  The French minister for European affairs was answering 
questions this afternoon in place of the foreign minister who is 
currently in Germany. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

