<F P=100> TURKEY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Spokesman Rejects Russian Criticism of Straits Rules </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Spokesman Rejects Russian Criticism of Straits Rules </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA0806155494 Ankara ANATOLIA in English 1515 GMT 8 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> TA0806155494 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara ANATOLIA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Ankara, June 8 (A.A.) -- Foreign Ministry Spokesman 
Ferhat Ataman said today that the straits regulations prepared 
and declared by Turkey have not been debated by the 
International Maritime Organization [IMO] and that the rejection 
of the regulations was out of the question. 
  He was reacting to a recent claim by the Russian Foreign 
Ministry that the IMO had not approved the proposals of Turkey 
on the straits and that Turkey was asked to adapt its 
regulations to the IMO resolutions. 
  Ataman said that it was not possible to share the Russian 
interpretation that the Turkish regulations were rejected by the 
IMO. 
  `The IMO Sea Safety Committee has reviewed and adopted all 
rules and recommendations for the passage of ships and traffic 
rules,' Ataman said. 
  Ataman recalled that the straits regulations were issued in 
the Official Gazette dated January 11, 1994 and the traffic 
charts were approved by the IMO. 
  `Turkey believes that the regulations to be put into force 
on 
July 1 and which are in harmony with the IMO regulations, 
contain all arrangements to provide security and environmental 
protection and are in the interests of all the countries and the 
world maritime,' he concluded. [sentence as received] 
  The straits regulations were prompted by the March 14 
collision in the Bosporus of an oil tanker and a freighter which 
killed 20 crew members and dumped thousands of barrels of oil 
into the waterway. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

