<H3> <TI>   NATO Communique Stresses Constructive Ties With Russia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    NATO Communique Stresses Constructive Ties With Russia </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA1006073494 Ankara TRT Television Network in Turkish 1700 
GMT 9 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA1006073494 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara TRT Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Turkish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Rahmi Aygun video report] </F>
  [Excerpt] [passage omitted] A joint communique was issued 
at the end of the NATO foreign ministers meeting in Istanbul 
today. The communique stated that an agreement was reached on 
Russia's importance for Europe. The statement expressed 
satisfaction over Russia's declaration of its intention to sign 
the Partnership for Peace agreement. The constructive relations 
between Russia and NATO will constitute the key element of 
confidence and stability in Europe, the communique noted. 
  Referring to regional issues, the communique described the 
cease-fire agreement to be enforced in Bosnia-Herzegovina for 
one month, beginning tomorrow, as a positive development. 
Pointing out that the alliance is open to other European 
countries as well, the statement declared that efforts will be 
exerted to prevent the proliferation of weapons of mass 
destruction. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

