<AU>   FBIS-WEU-94-112 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  9 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   NATO Members Comment on Relationship With Russia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    NATO Members Comment on Relationship With Russia </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA0906191194 Ankara ANATOLIA in English 1715 GMT 9 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> TA0906191194 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara ANATOLIA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Istanbul, June 9 (A.A.) -- NATO does not foresee 
any basic changes in the Conventional Forces in Europe [CFE] 
Reduction Treaty, except in a number of flexible articles of the 
agreement, it was reported on Thursday [9 June]. 
  Sources said that Russia would be involved in `far-reaching' 
but informal cooperation going beyond a simple Partnership for 
Peace accord. 
  U.S. Secretary of State Warren Christopher earlier said this 
was natural given `Russia's size, broad interests, resources and 
military capabilities.... Russia is and will remain a vital 
actor in European security affairs.' 
  `But Moscow must first sign a Partnership for Peace accord 
which 18 of its Cold War allies have already signed,' he added 
in his address. 
  The allies agreed to promise Russia cooperation and 
consultations outside a Partnership accord, notably nuclear 
safety and disarmament issues, sources said. 
  The allies invited Russian Foreign Minister Andrey Kozyrev 
to 
sign a Partnership accord soon at the NATO headquarters in 
Brussels, Belgium. Simultaneously, the two sides would then 
issue a declaration spelling out in detail their future 
cooperation, officials said. 
  Thursday's meeting opened with a promise to NATO's immediate 
neighbors to the east that the alliance has no plans to use 
Moscow to draw `new dividing lines across Europe' as happened at 
the February, 1945, Yalta conference by Russia, the United 
States and Britain. 
  NATO Deputy Secretary-General Sergio Balanzino said Russia 
`is and will remain the single most powerful nation in Europe.' 
But NATO has no intention to cooperate with Moscow `in 
so-called Yalta-2,' he added. 
  British Foreign Secretary Douglas Hurd said better relations 
with Moscow was `a matter of huge importance' as NATO seeks to 
craft a new European security order after the cold war. 
  The Partnership for Peace provides for broad political and 
military cooperation, including joint maneuvers. NATO will also 
help the East European nations draft defense budgets and convert 
arms industries to civilian purposes. It stops short of 
providing any security guarantees, but will allow for eventual 
NATO membership for some East European countries. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-42892 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drweu112aa_94004" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-WEU-94-112 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  9 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   UK: Relations of `Great Importance' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    UK: Relations of `Great Importance' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA0906170094 Ankara ANATOLIA in English 1620 GMT 9 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> TA0906170094 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara ANATOLIA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Istanbul, June 9 (A.A.) -- British Foreign 
Secretary Douglas Hurd said at the opening ceremony of the NATO 
foreign ministers meeting that the Cold War is over and now the 
time is coming for cooperation and partnership. 
  He said that relations with Russia have a great importance 
for NATO, expressing satisfaction upon the announcement by 
Russian Defense Minister Pavel Grachev that Russia will sign the 
Partnership for Peace [PFP] document. 
  Referring to a demand by Russia on `flexibility' within the 
document, Hurd said that the PFP has a very realistic character 
and it is large enough for including each country. 
  He also recalled words said earlier by Foreign Minister 
Hikmet Cetin, adding that NATO will make every effort for 
bringing lasting peace in Bosnia-Herzegovina. 

</TEXT>

