<H3> <TI>   Belgium Vows To Block EU Packaging Directive </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Belgium Vows To Block EU Packaging Directive </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BR0906132194 Groot-Bijgaarden DE STANDAARD in Dutch 9 Jun 94 
p 1 </F>

<F P=103> BR0906132194 </F>
<F P=104>  Groot-Bijgaarden DE STANDAARD </F>
<F P=105>  Dutch </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Article by Antoon Wouters: "Belgium Thwarting European </F>
Packaging Directive Today"] 
  [Excerpts] Belgium does not agree with the amendment by the 
European Parliament (EP) to the European Directive for packaging 
and packaging waste, and will oppose the directive. This was 
announced by Federal Environment Minister Jacques Santkin in 
Luxemburg yesterday. The issue will be discussed at the 
European Environment Council today. Germany, the Netherlands, 
and Denmark are also rejecting the directive. Santkin took the 
decision at the request of Flemish Environment Minister Norbert 
De Batselier, and after a verbal dispute at the interministerial 
foreign policy conference. 
  According to Santkin, the changes made by the EP to the 
directive, disturb the balance which was reached at the end of 
1993 between environmental protection and the safeguarding of 
the internal market. This compromise was reached thanks to the 
European Union's Belgian presidency. As a result of the 
directive's blocking, the Commission and the Environment 
Ministers will have to find a new compromise with the EP. 
[passage omitted] 
  De Batselier and Santkin fear that the amendment could 
jeopardize the Belgian ecological tax on disposable packagings. 
[passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

