<F P=101> Netherlands </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Purple' Coalition To Debate Defense Policy </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    `Purple' Coalition To Debate Defense Policy </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BR0906121494 Amsterdam DE VOLKSKRANT in Dutch 9 Jun 94 p 3 </F>
<F P=103> BR0906121494 </F>
<F P=104>  Amsterdam DE VOLKSKRANT </F>
<F P=105>  Dutch </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Liberals To Oppose Defense Cuts"] </F>
  [Text] The VVD [People's Party for Freedom and Democracy] 
has great difficulty in accepting cuts of 300 million guilders 
[G] in the defense budget, a legacy of the present government. 
The VVD wants to reduce these cutbacks to zero. The PvdA 
[Labor Party] on the other hand wants to see even more defense 
cuts, of as much as G1.4 billion in all. 
  The three party leaders who are negotiating to form a 
"purple" coalition government comprising the PvdA, the VVD, and 
D66 [Democrats 66] are today to discuss defense policy. 
  In the election program, the Liberals position was that 
defense should be spared any cutbacks. But, since the present 
government is leaving behind it a "hole" of G5 billion, the VVD 
may also be unable to escape defense cuts. 
  In the election campaign, the VVD referred to this legacy of 
the present government as "[outgoing Finance Minister] Kok's 
hole." On calculating the cost of the election programs of all 
parties, the Central Planning Bureau concluded that all 
ministries would have to contribute to the G5 billion shortfall. 
The VVD later regretted that this "cheese-slicing method" also 
involved defense. 
  D66 also ran an election campaign in which defense was to be 
spared any cuts. But the Democrats have now reconciled 
themselves to a maximum of G600 million being cut from the 
defense budget. 
  The only conclusion reached by talks on public health, 
pursued by the three party leaders yesterday, is that there are 
to be no major changes to the system. PvdA leader Kok reported 
that the negotiators agreed that a "practical, businesslike 
approach" must be adopted to achieve costs management in the 
health sector. 
  Kok said that "no negotiating took place yesterday." 
Instead, 
the negotiators drew up a list of "major questions" to which the 
public health experts from the three parties must find an answer. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

