<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Waigel Calls For Coordinated EU Tax Rate </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Waigel Calls For Coordinated EU Tax Rate </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0906160694 Duesseldorf HANDELSBLATT in German 9 Jun 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> AU0906160694 </F>
<F P=104>  Duesseldorf HANDELSBLATT </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["vwd"-attributed report: "Escape Routes to Europe Should </F>
Be Blocked"] 
  [Excerpt] During the forthcoming European Parliament 
consultations, Finance Minister Theo Waigel wants to attain 
political agreement on the gradual attainment of a joint 
European tax rate on interest rates during Germany's duty 
presidency of the European Union [EU]. Only with a coordinated 
tax rate can the outflow of German capital to other countries be 
prevented, a phenomenon that has been observed ever since the 
introduction of tax on interest rates in Germany. 
  In an interview with this writer, Waigel said the subject 
will not be finally settled while Germany holds the presidency, 
"but we will probably reach political decisions that can be 
implemented. One cannot place excess demands on others. 
Negotiations on this matter can be continued under France's EU 
presidency." 
  Waigel spoke out in favor of pursuing the principle of 
subsidiarity. He said there is a compulsory tax on interest 
rates in every EU country, but each country applies a different 
tax system. "Things should remain that way," said Waigel. "All 
we are concerned with is preventing a citizen of one country 
from evading this tax by going to another country. Such an 
evasion would not lie in any country's interests." The finance 
minister spoke out in favor of including as many OECD countries 
as possible in a suitable agreement. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

