<F P=100> TURKEY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Cetin Discusses Iraqi Pipeline With UK's Hurd </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Cetin Discusses Iraqi Pipeline With UK's Hurd </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA0906191494 Ankara ANATOLIA in Turkish 1700 GMT 9 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> TA0906191494 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara ANATOLIA </F>
<F P=105>  Turkish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Istanbul (AA) -- Foreign Minister Hikmet Cetin has 
said that Turkey is justified regarding its requests concerning 
the Karkuk-Yumurtalik pipeline. 
  Cetin was speaking after his 50-minute meeting with British 
Foreign Secretary Douglas Hurd held during the North Atlantic 
Council meetings in Istanbul today. He said that he told his 
British counterpart that Turkey's sole aim is to save the 
pipeline. Cetin continued: 
  I explained to him that this cannot be compared to other 
countries' relations with Iraq, that it is a very special 
problem, and that we are justified in trying to save the 
pipeline. 
  Cetin noted that relations with the European Union [EU] were 
also discussed in detail at the meeting. 
  Recalling that Germany and France will be chairing the EU 
meetings consecutively as of July, Cetin said: We view this 
period as a significant one in Turkey's relations with the 
Customs Union as well as the EU. 
  Cetin stated that the situation in Iraq and the 
Azerbaijani-Armenian clashes were also discussed at the meeting. 
  Pointing out that they also dwelt on the benefits of 
extending the tripartite meetings process among Turkey, Britain, 
and Germany to include France as well, Cetin concluded by saying 
that the tripartite meetings can be converted into quadripartite 
ones. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

