<DOCNO> FBIS4-42939 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drweu112_q_94004" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-WEU-94-112 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  5 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> TURKEY </F>
<H3> <TI>   EU Warned on Admitting `South' Cyprus as Member </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    EU Warned on Admitting `South' Cyprus as Member </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC0906201694 Istanbul HURRIYET in Turkish 5 Jun 94 p 19 </F>
<F P=103> NC0906201694 </F>
<F P=104>  Istanbul HURRIYET </F>
<F P=105>  Turkish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Selin Caglayan report: "Ankara Warns European Union on </F>
Cyprus"] 
  [Text] Ankara--While Greece maintains its pressure on the 
European Union [EU] to have south Cyprus admitted into that 
organization as a member, Ankara has warned the EU countries 
that they "will have to accept the consequences of south Cyprus 
becoming an EU member and that such a development will mark the 
end of the negotiating process in Cyprus." 
  It has been reported that the messages Ankara has conveyed 
to 
the EU countries at various levels can be taken to mean that the 
TRNC [Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus] will unite with 
Turkey if the Greek Cypriot side is admitted into the EU as a 
full member. Turkey defends the view that the Greek Cypriot side 
becoming an EU member will mean the de facto annexation of south 
Cyprus to Greece. 
  Meanwhile, a number of officials in Turkey have maintained 
that several points in UN Secretary General Butrus 
Butrus-Ghali's report on Cyprus, which has elicited strong 
reaction in Turkey, can be justified. A Turkish Foreign 
Ministry official has said that the fact that Butrus 
Butrus-Ghali has agreed that the Cyprus problem has continued 
for 30 years is "a very positive development." The Greek 
Cypriots have maintained that the Cyprus problem was created as 
a result of Turkey's intervention in the island in 1974. 
Furthermore, Ankara has regarded Butrus-Ghali's view that "the 
limited UN resources may be used to resolve other disputes" as a 
positive suggestion. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-42940 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drweu112_q_94005" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-WEU-94-112 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  10 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> TURKEY </F>
<H3> <TI>   UN Forces Mandate Triggers `Harsh Reaction' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    UN Forces Mandate Triggers `Harsh Reaction' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA1006092394 Ankara Turkiye Radyolari Network in Turkish 
0430 GMT 10 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA1006092394 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara Turkiye Radyolari Network </F>
<F P=105>  Turkish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Yavuz Baydar in New York] </F>
  [Excerpt] [passage omitted] The report issued by the UN 
secretary general yesterday on the extension of the UNFICYP [UN 
Forces in Cyprus] mandate triggered harsh reaction both from 
Turkey and the Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus [TRNC]. 
Ambassador Inal Batu, Turkey's permanent representative to the 
United Nations, described this new report as a text by the UN 
secretary general that ignores the wishes of the Turkish side on 
the island. 
  Osman Ertug, TRNC representative in New York, said that the 
report pours salt on the wounds. Turkish Cypriot officials say 
that the report, like the previous one, is politically oriented, 
whereas it should have been primarily a technical report. 
  Ertug said: In our view, the fact that the accusation 
concerning the lack of political will is directed -- even though 
only by implication -- against the Turkish Cypriot side 
constitutes the most dangerous factor in the report. 

</TEXT>

