<H3> <TI>   Demirel Expresses Continued Support </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Demirel Expresses Continued Support </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA0906181094 Ankara ANATOLIA in English 1710 GMT 9 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> TA0906181094 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara ANATOLIA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Istanbul, June 9 (A.A.) -- President Suleyman 
Demirel on Thursday [9 June] said that Azerbaijan has suffered 
great losses from the Armenian invasion, adding responsible 
countries should not remain spectators to this situation. 
  He called it a crime against humanity that the country 
should 
be left in this situation adding that 1.2 million people have 
become refugees and that a very harsh winter has led to heavy 
losses. 
  Demirel said that it is unacceptable that a country seizes 
another country's territories by force and in this situation it 
is impossible that Turkey establish good relations with the 
invading country, Armenia. 
  He said Turkey will take steps to bring peace in the region 
and will continue to voice the injustices done to Azerbaijan, 
adding he will take up the issues during his meeting with U.S. 
Secretary of State Warren Christopher. 
  Azerbaijani President Geydar Aliyev said that a number of 
agreements have been signed with two friendly countries Turkey 
and Azerbaijan and that bilateral high level meetings are also 
contributing to the development of relations. 

</TEXT>

