<F P=100> TURKEY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Cetin Meets Christopher, Rejects Aid Linkage </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Cetin Meets Christopher, Rejects Aid Linkage </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA1006115994 Ankara TRT Television Network in Turkish 1000 
GMT 10 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA1006115994 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara TRT Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Turkish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Announcer-read report over video] </F>
  [Excerpts] Foreign Minister Hikmet Cetin is continuing his 
bilateral contacts with foreign ministers who are currently in 
Istanbul for the North Atlantic Cooperation Council meetings. 
This morning, Cetin met with U.S. Secretary of State Warren 
Christopher. 
  In a joint statement issued with Christopher, Cetin said 
that 
bilateral relations, the Cyprus problem, the oil pipeline, and 
issues such as the Azerbaijani-Armenian conflict were discussed 
during the meeting. [passage omitted] 
  In a statement he issued later, Cetin declared that the U.S. 
House of Representatives decision to cut aid to Turkey is 
unacceptable. 
  [Begin Cetin recording] I informed Christopher that linking 
25 percent of aid to certain conditions is unacceptable to the 
Turkish public and the Turkish Government and that the U.S. 
Administration must use the necessary influence in the coming 
days to rectify this. I also expressed Turkey's satisfaction 
that the request concerning 10 [word indistinct] planes has been 
referred to the U.S. Congress. Moreover, we discussed the need 
for the U.S. Administration to continue its efforts for the 
positive conclusion of this matter in Congress. [end recording] 
  Cetin explained that in principle, Christopher was positive 
about the Karkuk-Yumurtalik oil pipeline issue, and the work on 
this subject will continue in the coming days. The conflict 
between Azerbaijan and Armenia was also discussed during the 
talks, Cetin reported, adding that it would be wrong to take the 
issue to platforms other than the CSCE. 
  Cetin later met with Finnish Foreign Minister Heikki 
Haavisto. Bilateral political and economic relations were 
discussed during the meeting. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

