<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Italy Must Push a Bit More, </F>
Christophersen Says"] 
  [Text] (ANSA) Brussels, May 25 -- Price and exchange rate 
stability, achieved by reducing the inflation rate by no more 
than 2-3 percent by 1996, were among the primary objectives 
indicated by the European Commission to member states, including 
Italy, in a program document outlined here today by Commissioner 
Henning Christophersen. 
  While several countries have already reached the inflation 
rates indicated by the Commission, Italy, Spain, Portugal and 
Britain must do more to bring down inflation in their countries, 
he said. However, Christophersen added that he expected both 
Italy and Britain to be able to get their inflation rates 
significantly closer to the limits indicated by the Commission 
by next year. 
  The commissioner saw more rigid fiscal policies as the way 
to 
achieve that consolidation of national budgets called for in 
convergence programs. Here again Italy must make an additional 
effort to re-structure its tax system, finding alternative ways 
to bring in revenue -- such as the eco-tax, for example, so as 
to promote employment and not overburden the labor force, he 
said. 
  Christophersen said it was "unacceptable" that unemployment 
levels remained high even in the presence of economic recovery 
like that observed in numerous European nations. 
  Given the recovery, he said it was "illogical" that 
long-term 
interest rates continue rising and he insisted that it was 
necessary to combat this tendency through structural adjustments 
and interventions on the job market so as to the raise the 
growth rate from the present 1.6 percent to 2.5 percent in 1995. 
  Christophersen would not be drawn on the question of when 
Italy might return to the European Monetary System but defined 
as "ambitious" the Italian government's project to create one 
million jobs. Although he admitted he did not know how the 
Berlusconi government planned to achieve this goal, 
Christophersen said that ambitious governments were a good thing 
to have. 

</TEXT>

