<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Germany </F>
<H3> <TI>   Naumann Recalls Russian World War II Sacrifices </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Naumann Recalls Russian World War II Sacrifices </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0706075494 Hamburg DPA in German 2021 GMT 6 Jun 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU0706075494 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Augsburg (DPA) -- Bundeswehr Inspector General 
Klaus Naumann has come out in favor of not forgetting Russia's 
contribution on the occasion of the 50th anniversary of the end 
of World War II next year. In an interview with AUGSBURGER 
ALLGEMEINE (Tuesday [7 June] edition), Naumann said that a 
celebration with Russia "is not my decision." But one "should 
not forget the contribution and the sacrifices made by Russia to 
destroy fascism and to end the war, even though Moscow's goal 
was the establishment of another dictatorship." 
  Concerning accusations of antisemitic and xenophobic 
statements by drunk Guard Battalion soldiers, as well as the 
arrest of a noncommissioned officer for being the head of a 
defense sports group, Naumann said that he does not observe any 
intensified influx of right-wing extremists in the Bundeswehr. 
Last year 53 such cases were reported, in which 63 soldiers 
were involved, 80 percent of them conscripts. "I think that the 
fact that there were only 53 cases among 390,000 soldiers in 
1993 contradicts the impression of a shift to the right." 

</TEXT>

