<H3> <TI>   Kohl, Mitterrand Meet in Heidelberg 8 Jun </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kohl, Mitterrand Meet in Heidelberg 8 Jun </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Kohl Stresses `Close Partnership' </H4>

<F P=102> AU0806144494 Hamburg DPA in German 1247 GMT 8 Jun 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU0806144494 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Bonn -- Shortly before his meeting with French 
President Francois Mitterrand and young people from both 
countries in Heidelberg, Chancellor Helmut Kohl emphatically 
stressed the close partnership between the two states. The youth 
festival in the old university town, in which 6,000 people will 
participate, should be a "festival of joy" two days after the 
celebrations marking the 50th anniversary of the landing of the 
Allied forces in Normandy, Kohl told DPA. 
  The chancellor again reaffirmed that at no point he 
expressed 
the wish to participate in the ceremonies of the allies. "I do 
not believe that the German chancellor should have been in 
Normandy that day." However, on the occasion of the 
anniversary, he and Mitterrand thought about what the French and 
the Germans could do to make it clear that the French and the 
German peoples have become friends "50 years afterward." 
  The deliberations led to the idea to organize a "festival of 
joy and friendship" with young people from both countries in 
Heidelberg. "We want to make it clear that we do not forget 
history, but that we want to learn from history," Kohl stated. 
Without the close partnership and friendship between France and 
Germany, a peaceful future in Europe is inconceivable. 

</TEXT>

